<subSubSection id="C36D7687747FFFFAFF14F8B6FD31FED7" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC8250C747FFFFAFF14F8B6FD31FED7" blockId="7.[151,1437,1795,2036]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="166" pageId="7" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis id="B903F91E747FFFF5FF14F8B6FE91F8A1" bold="true" box="[151,273,1795,1820]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Metope wide, with distinct median carina running from its upper margin to metopoclypeal suture and very weak sublateral carinae visible only in its upper part and joined median carina below upper margin of metope (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD747FFFF5FF1DF8FEFD80F8D9" box="[158,512,1867,1892]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 3</bibRefCitation>
); lateral margins convex. Coryphe transverse, 1.5 times as wide as long at midline, with weak incomplete median carina (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD747FFFF5FDC6F8DAFC2CF835" box="[581,940,1903,1928]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 1</bibRefCitation>
). Second and third segments of rostrum are almost equal in length; third segment narrowing apically. Fore wings elongate, surpassing abdominal apex, with narrow hypocostal plate. Forewing vein sequence: R 2, furcating very close to basal cell; M 3, first furcation in basal third of the wing, second furcation in apical third; CuΑ 1 (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD747FFFF5FC01F86EFB74F849" box="[898,1268,2011,2036]" pageId="7" pageNumber="165" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 2</bibRefCitation>
). Clavus long, open—Pcu+Α1 runs into apex of clavus. Pcu fusing Α1 after middle of clavus (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFB9EFF22FA0BFF0D" box="[1053,1419,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6203" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. &amp; Poggi, F. (2014) First record of Nearctic issid planthopper Thionia simplex (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea: Issidae) from Europe. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 238 - 241." type="journal article">Gnezdilov &amp; Poggi 2014, fig. 1</bibRefCitation>
). Hind wings 3-lobed, with deep cubital cleft and without coupling lobe on its anterior margin (
<figureCitation id="134C39897470FFFAFB3FFF0BFA8FFF6A" box="[1212,1295,190,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–11" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1322,1345]" captionTargetBox="[533,1060,201,1303]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[525,1074,195,1311]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 9–11. Thioniina, hind wing. 9—Cheiloceps musca Uhler; 10—Cheiloceps argo (Fennah); 11—Aplos simplex (Germar). Abbreviations: rl—remigial lobe; rvl—remigio-vannal lobe; al—anal lobe." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1290890/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Hind wing vein sequence: R 2 r-m 1 M 1 m-cua 1 CuΑ 2 cua-cup 1 CuP 1 cup-pcu 1 Pcu 3 pcu-a1 1 Α1 2 Α2 2. Hind tibia with 2 lateral spines in its apical half. First metatarsomere with a whole row of spines arranged in arc. Dorso-lateral phallobase lobes fused dorsally, poorly sclerotized apically. Each dorso-lateral phallobase lobe with a large hookshaped apical process (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFE1BFEE4FD24FED7" box="[408,676,337,362]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5415" refString="Doering, K. C. (1938) A contribution to the taxonomy of the subfamily Issinae in America north of Mexico (Fulgoridae, Homoptera). Part 2. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 25 (20), 447 - 575." type="journal article">Doering 1938, Pl. 55: 2</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36D76877470FFFAFF44FEC0FEB3FDFF" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC8250C7470FFFAFF44FEC0FB1BFE33" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" box="[199,1179,373,398]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis id="B903F91E7470FFFAFF44FEC0FECEFE33" bold="true" box="[199,334,373,398]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Etymology.</emphasis>
Generic name derived from Greek “Απλός” (simple). Masculine in gender.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC8250C7470FFFAFF44FE2CFEB3FDFF" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,578]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis id="B903F91E7470FFFAFF44FE2CFEE7FE0F" bold="true" box="[199,359,409,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Composition.</emphasis>
Αpparently 
<taxonomicName id="4C775E8F7470FFFAFE71FE2CFCA8FE0F" authority="(Say, 1830)" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[498,808,409,434]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Thionia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullata">
<emphasis id="B903F91E7470FFFAFE71FE2CFD1FFE0F" box="[498,671,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Thionia bullata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFD2CFE2FFC9FFE0F" box="[687,799,410,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6575" refString="Say, T. (1830) Descriptions of new North American hemipterous insects, belonging to the first family of the section Homoptera of Latreille. Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 6, 235 - 244." type="journal article">Say, 1830</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(originally 
<taxonomicName id="4C775E8F7470FFFAFC2FFE2CFB35FE0F" authority="Say, 1830" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1830" box="[940,1205,409,434]" class="Insecta" family="Flatidae" genus="Flata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bullata">
<emphasis id="B903F91E7470FFFAFC2FFE2CFBBFFE0F" box="[940,1087,409,434]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">Flata bullata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFBC5FE2FFB35FE0F" box="[1094,1205,410,434]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref6575" refString="Say, T. (1830) Descriptions of new North American hemipterous insects, belonging to the first family of the section Homoptera of Latreille. Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 6, 235 - 244." type="journal article">Say, 1830</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) also belongs to this genus according to the structure of phallobase bearing hook-shaped apical process, however, this species differs from the type species by furcating subapically ventral aedeagal hooks (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFC58FE54FA83FE47" box="[987,1283,481,506]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5415" refString="Doering, K. C. (1938) A contribution to the taxonomy of the subfamily Issinae in America north of Mexico (Fulgoridae, Homoptera). Part 2. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 25 (20), 447 - 575." type="journal article">Doering 1938, Pl. 55: 10</bibRefCitation>
) and distinct sublateral carinae of metope (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE658FD7470FFFAFE62FDB0FD37FDA3" box="[481,695,517,542]" pageId="8" pageNumber="166" refId="ref5213" refString="Bartlett, C. R., O'Brien, L. B. &amp; Wilson, S. W. (2014) A review of the planthoppers (Hemiptera: Fulgoroidea) of the United States. Memoires of the American Entomological Society, 50, 1 - 187." type="journal article">
Bartlett 
<emphasis id="B903F91E7470FFFAFDBEFDB3FDEEFDA3" box="[573,622,517,542]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="166">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 86D). The correct taxonomic position of this species needs to be confirmed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
